<h3 align="center"><strong>INSPIRATION AND LEMONADE:</strong></h3>
<p align="center"><strong>The story behind Beyond the Misty Shore</strong></p>
<p align="center"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p align="center"><strong>By</strong></p>
<p align="center"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p align="center"><strong>Vicki Hinze</strong></p>
<h3 align="center"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></h3>
<h3>Into every life, lemon juice does pour.&nbsp; If you&rsquo;re lucky, you learn to love lemonade. I&rsquo;m lucky. And it&rsquo;s a good thing because&hellip;</h3>
<h3>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3>I was having a pitcher-full and a truth about life and lemonade settled in:&nbsp; Loving lemonade is a choice.&nbsp; I mean, we can&rsquo;t avoid lemon juice any more than we can avoid challenges. We can fight it, but we are going to lose. Lemon juice will be poured; it&rsquo;s inevitable. But that doesn&rsquo;t mean it has to be bitter. We can make a different choice. Sprinkle in a little sugar or Splenda, so to speak, a little water, and we&rsquo;ve got lemonade, which tastes quite good and, on a hot day, it&rsquo;s amazingly refreshing.</h3>
<h3>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3>So I got juiced. I was at this crossroad in my life, debating which way to go, and this lemonade truth kept stealing my attention. I refilled my glass with half-a-pitcher to go, and another thought came to mind.&nbsp; We have a choice. When life throws us lemons, we can choose to make lemonade, or not. Another thought chased that one:</h3>
<h3>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3><em>What if we couldn&rsquo;t?</em></h3>
<h3>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3>What if we didn&rsquo;t have a choice. Or the choice wasn&rsquo;t ours to make. We&rsquo;d be stuck. Literally swimming in lemon juice without lemonade or a solution or resolution in sight!</h3>
<h3>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3>I didn&rsquo;t care for the feeling, and it shot holes in my theory that I had at least a little control in my life. Don&rsquo;t you hate it when that happens?&nbsp; When your illusions are shattered and as leaky as a sieve?</h3>
<h3>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3>I more than didn&rsquo;t like it, I hated it&hellip;but I was intrigued. So I thought about it.&nbsp; Okay, so you have not a pitcher full of lemon juice but a barrel full. You&rsquo;re already banged up.&nbsp; (Can anyone get to adulthood in life without getting banged up?&nbsp; Unlikely.&nbsp; Rare, even.) So you&rsquo;re chugging lemon juice from the barrel, eager to drain it and get the nastiness behind you.&nbsp; You&rsquo;ve deciphered your problems and have progressed to looking for solutions, and you&rsquo;re feeling good about that because, while the bad stuff isn&rsquo;t behind you yet, you&rsquo;ve made progress.&nbsp; You&rsquo;re on your way to getting rid of it.</h3>
<h3>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3>Only you&rsquo;re not. You&rsquo;ve wracked your brain and there just are no solutions. Not even one. Worse, not only have you been robbed of a solution, your choice in what to do has been stolen, too.&nbsp; <em>Now what?&nbsp; What do you do?</em></h3>
<h3><em>&nbsp;</em></h3>
<h3>That was the situation I found myself in that led me to write the Seascape novels, and <strong><em>Beyond the Misty Shore</em></strong>specifically.</h3>
<h3>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3>Being stuck doesn&rsquo;t exactly inspire you to be in the most receptive frame of mind. Sunshine is arrogant when you&rsquo;re grieving, right? But isn&rsquo;t it true that the worst possible time is always when important things happen? When life-changing things happen?</h3>
<h3>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3>That&rsquo;s been true in my life, and so I made it true in TJ MacGregor&rsquo;s life, too.&nbsp; He is the hero stuck at Seascape Inn in Beyond the Misty Shore.&nbsp; Add more lemon juice in the form of Maggie Wright, a woman who loves to hate him, and Miss Hattie, the wise Seascape innkeeper (who seems to know <em>everything</em> about everything but won&rsquo;t just tell anyone anything because &ldquo;some things are best learned firsthand&rdquo;), a colorful cast of local characters, Maine cliffs, and a little otherworldly intervention, and, well, T.J. has his work cut out for him, doesn&rsquo;t he?</h3>
<h3>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3>He did, and so did I. But don&rsquo;t feel too bad for him.&nbsp; We&rsquo;ve all tasted the tart of the juice and, you know, sometimes when we&rsquo;re broken, we have to <em>really</em> hurt to ever get beyond the pain. We have to figure out that we can heal before we do heal.</h3>
<h3>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3>Eventually, we get it. And when we do, magic happens. We no longer just survive. We truly live.</h3>
<h3>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3>Like you and me, he&rsquo;ll figure it out&hellip; eventually. So will Maggie.&nbsp; And what fun to watch without personally sucking lemons!</h3>
<h3>&nbsp;</h3>
<h3>I&rsquo;m getting a little misty here. I think I&rsquo;ll pack a bag and go visit Seascape Inn again . . . just as soon as I finish this glass of lemonade.&nbsp; Care to join me?</h3>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h3>That&#8217;s not a rhetorical invitation but a real one. &nbsp;My publisher, Bell Bridge Books, is giving away digital copies of&nbsp;<em>Beyond the Misty Shore</em> right now. You can get a free copy at <a href="http://www.amazon.com/Beyond-The-Misty-Shore-ebook/dp/B005WECDJA/ref=sr_1_11?s=digital-text&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1362586014&amp;sr=1-11&amp;keywords=Vicki+Hinze" target="_blank">Amazon</a>, <a href="http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/beyond-the-misty-shore-vicki-hinze/1106699722?ean=9781611940541" target="_blank">Nook</a>, <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/us/book/beyond-the-misty-shore/id475239505?mt=11" target="_blank">iBooks</a>, <a href="http://www.kobobooks.com/ebook/Beyond-The-Misty-Shore/book-Pkvq4jBPMEWTk-B98DWz8Q/page1.html?s=enZhOyk4IUGYgKOSLdXLDQ&amp;r=10" target="_blank">Kobo</a>, or <a href="https://play.google.com/store/books/details/Vicki_Hinze_Beyond_the_Misty_Shore?id=apaZsPmGxJsC&amp;feature=search_result" target="_blank">Google Play</a> in the US, UK, Canada or Australia.</h3>
